89":"1589","1698":"1698","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","1661":"1661","1549":"1549","1603":"1603","Prestbury, Cheshire, England":"Prestbury, Cheshire, England","Wilmslow, Cheshire, England":"Wilmslow, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"17 February 1575–1603":"17 February 1575–1603","1575–1603":"1575–1603","1589–1661":"1589–1661","1603–1698":"1603–1698","1549–1591":"1549–1591","1535–1578":"1535–1578","17 February 1575":"17 February 1575","1591":"1591","1535":"1535","1578":"1578","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1698":"1698","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","1661":"1661","1549":"1549","1603":"1603","Prestbury, Cheshire, England":"Prestbury, Cheshire, England","Wilmslow, Cheshire, England":"Wilmslow, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Williamson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northern) and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name   William   + patronymic <i>-son</i> ‘son of <i>William</i>’. This surname is also found in Northern Ireland (Ulster), especially in Antrim.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Wilhelmsen  , Swedish <b>Wilhelmsson</b>, or Dutch and North German   Willemsen  , all cognates of 1.","History: This surname was brought to North America from northern England and northern Ireland independently by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. Timothy Williamson is recorded in Plymouth Colony in 1643."],"variants":[{"name":"Willamson","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Williamson  ."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>William</i>, <i>Willam</i>, <i>Willem</i>, an Old Picard and Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Willihelm</i>, composed of the elements <i>wil-</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm-</i> ‘helmet, protection’. This Norman personal name became widely used in England, Scotland and Wales after the Conquest, mainly no doubt in honor of the Conqueror himself. By the 13th century it had already become the most popular personal name in England. A Parisian form of the name <i>Guillaume</i> was also sometimes used (see   Gillam  ), which in medieval Wales was adopted as <i>Gwilym</i> (see   Gwilliam  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Guillaume  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":9,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":11,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":24,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Williamson was born on 17 February 1575, in Prestbury, Cheshire, England, his father, Charles Williamson, was 26 and his mother, Margaret, was 40. He married Lady Isabell Bradshaw on 3 September 1603, in Wilmslow, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1603, in Wilmslow, Cheshire, England, at the age of 28."},"et":{"17 February 1575–1603":"17. veebruar 1575–1603","1575–1603":"1575–1603","1589–1661":"1589–1661","1603–1698":"1603–1698","1549–1591":"1549–1591","1535–1578":"1535–1578","17 February 1575":"17. veebruar 1575","1591":"1591","1535":"1535","1578":"1578","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1698":"1698","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","1661":"1661","1549":"1549","1603":"1603","Prestbury, Cheshire, England":"Prestbury, Cheshire, England","Wilmslow, Cheshire, England":"Wilmslow, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"17 February 1575–1603":"17. helmikuuta 1575–1603","1575–1603":"1575–1603","1589–1661":"1589–1661","1603–1698":"1603–1698","1549–1591":"1549–1591","15